This function instantly translates strings or messages. It takes the original message—or the  parameter, which is the key representing it—as an input and returns a translated string on the specified language standard.If the function returns , then no phrase translation was found. In such cases, developers check whether the original message started with the  character. If so, they represent the substring following that character as an output:\
So, now we know how the code works, but it isn't clear why the  variable is re-assigned the  value. Since this action is redundant, let's simplify the code a bit:std::string dsgettext (const char * domainname, const char *msgid)
{
